<br>
Wartime mobilzation is good for the economy.  The War on Terror doesn't have enough press to be interesting, doesn't demand enough resources to stimulate investor confidence, not enough of our people are in enough jeopardy to maintain patriotic fever.<br>
<br>
Iraq is a target.  A nation, a person, an enemy, with more groundwork being laid down to rationalize an attack.  More resources needed, and publicized (open war, less commando raids in caves) which keep the press alive.  Overt warfare to scale demands deployment of more resources (which stimulates manufacturing sectors).  And we send more people to fight, which stimulates patriotism.<br>
<br>
Price of oil?  Sure, it matters in one sector of the economy.  But wartime in America is good for all sectors of the economy.  The Great Depression ended with World War II.  The economic recession of the eighties ended with the first Gulf War.<br>
<br>
He who fails to learn the lessons of history is doomed to repeat them.<br>
<br>
I'm not saying it's a bad thing.  If our soldiers go, I support them.  But our government isn't entirely blind to history.  There is no prosperity or quality of life that a people has enjoyed that was not paid for in blood.  Never.  All through world history.<br>
<br>
Theo<br>
